Because the date of the trip may be five years after winning the fund.

28
00:01:53,860 --> 00:01:56,740
Indeed.

29
00:01:57,380 --> 00:02:04,660
The other thing that Claire mentioned is that she very carefully stores all of her Hugo finalist pins together

30
00:02:04,660 --> 00:02:09,860
and knows precisely where they are, which is extremely organised.

31
00:02:09,860 --> 00:02:15,400
Alison, do you have any relevant anecdotes about Hugo pins and the care thereof?

32
00:02:15,400 --> 00:02:23,140
Well, I was thinking about the care of Hugo pins because I have a neighbour who makes giant public artworks

33
00:02:23,140 --> 00:02:28,520
out of little mosaic tiles and she normally generates these tiles in big community workshops

34
00:02:28,520 --> 00:02:30,280
and I've never quite managed to get to one of them.

35
00:02:30,280 --> 00:02:34,360
These are beautiful and I will put a link to them on the show notes and you can be amazed.

36
00:02:34,360 --> 00:02:36,640
They are exactly what public art should be like.

37
00:02:36,640 --> 00:02:42,880
And in lockdown, she worked, she started off being a bit depressed that she couldn't have these big community workshops

38
00:02:42,880 --> 00:02:46,680
and then she realised that she could roll out a lot of tiny little mosaic tiles

39
00:02:46,680 --> 00:02:51,460
and put them in boxes wet for local families to pick up

40
00:02:51,460 --> 00:02:56,140
and then stamp out the tiles using tools they find around the house and then return them.

41
00:02:56,140 --> 00:02:59,460
And so I have stamped out a load of tiles with a load of things around the house

42
00:02:59,460 --> 00:03:03,160
that are important to me and to my family, including one of my Hugo pins.

43
00:03:03,160 --> 00:03:04,320
Clay is inert.

44
00:03:04,320 --> 00:03:05,720
It won't have done any permanent damage.

45
00:03:05,720 --> 00:03:09,340
It does have quite a bit of clay on it now, but, you know, I think that'll be OK.

46
00:03:09,340 --> 00:03:14,540
Not only do I not keep my Hugo pins carefully, but I did manage to find one.

47
00:03:14,540 --> 00:03:17,460
So I thought that was quite good and I will brush the clay off it.

48
00:03:17,460 --> 00:03:22,100
But I also don't tend to look after them very well, for which I'm sorry.

49
00:03:22,100 --> 00:03:24,980
I know it's very important and I should be very grateful.

50
00:03:24,980 --> 00:03:27,200
I mean, I'm very grateful of the pin.

51
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:32,360
And my other Hugo abuse anecdote is that, of course, the very first thing I did after winning Hugo,

52
00:03:32,360 --> 00:03:36,500
apart from brandishing it on an upper deck of a bus, was play ring toss with it.

53
00:03:36,500 --> 00:03:41,600
Did you get a bus tour of London when you won a Hugo, like the cricket team?

54
00:03:41,600 --> 00:03:45,200
We got a bus tour of Glasgow, which is just as good.

55
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:46,360
Ah, it's amazing.

56
00:03:46,360 --> 00:03:47,100
I didn't know that.

57
00:03:47,100 --> 00:03:50,120
We won the Hugos at the SECC.

58
00:03:50,120 --> 00:03:52,880
The party was somewhere else in Glasgow.

59
00:03:52,880 --> 00:03:55,200
Was it in the party hotel in Glasgow?

60
00:03:55,200 --> 00:03:56,640
It was in the party hotel.

61
00:03:56,640 --> 00:03:59,000
And so we got driven by a double-decker bus.

62
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,640
So the Plotka Bowl were on the top of the double-decker bus waving our Hugos around.

63
00:04:02,640 --> 00:04:05,660
And George R. R. Martin was there waving his Hugo around.

64
00:04:05,660 --> 00:04:08,780
And I asked him where the next book was coming out, which was probably very bad.

65
00:04:08,780 --> 00:04:11,160
And the next book did come out, but not the one after.

66
00:04:11,160 --> 00:04:12,220
So, you know, there we go.

67
00:04:12,220 --> 00:04:18,340
And then we went to the Hugo party and it was full of authors and kind of a bit dreary.

68
00:04:18,340 --> 00:04:22,100
And so we came back to the fan lounge in the motor house next to the SECC,

69
00:04:22,100 --> 00:04:23,720
which is really where we should have been all along.

70
00:04:23,720 --> 00:04:27,480
But we wouldn't have wanted to miss out on riding around on the top of the bus.

71
00:04:27,780 --> 00:04:31,480
Obviously, the population of Glasgow came out and threw ticket a patters.

72
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:34,040
No, they did not.

73
00:04:34,040 --> 00:04:35,260
But we imagined it.

74
00:04:35,260 --> 00:04:36,220
Fair enough.

75
00:04:36,220 --> 00:04:38,920
It was one of the best nights of my life, I have to say.

76
00:04:38,920 --> 00:04:40,860
I strongly recommend Winnie Cugos.

77
00:04:40,860 --> 00:04:45,460
I think I also played ring toss at the 2005 Worldcon.

78
00:04:45,460 --> 00:04:51,100
I think I was standing kind of on the balcony around the lobby of the party hotel in Glasgow,

79
00:04:51,100 --> 00:04:54,680
whose name I have forgotten, with a bunch of, I think they were like glow sticks

80
00:04:54,680 --> 00:04:56,980
and trying to throw them at people down in the lobby.

81
00:04:56,980 --> 00:04:58,560
Didn't do that very long, though.

82
00:04:58,560 --> 00:05:01,040
I mean, I think the glow sticks rings a bell because I was like,

83
00:05:01,040 --> 00:05:02,340
well, what were we using for the rings?

84
00:05:02,340 --> 00:05:03,880
And I think it was, in fact, glow sticks.

85
00:05:03,880 --> 00:05:07,880
So I think we must have had those little glow sticks that you clipped together and pushed out.

86
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:13,460
Somebody, somebody who's a proper fan historian is going to remember this in some detail and write to us.

87
00:05:13,460 --> 00:05:16,180
I suspect it will be one Claire Braley of Croydon.

88
00:05:17,920 --> 00:05:23,440
Before we end the anecdote, I should say I was throwing the glow ring at someone who was expecting me to throw the glow ring at them,

89
00:05:23,440 --> 00:05:27,720
not at, like, completely random people standing in the hotel lobby, which would not be correct.

90
00:05:27,720 --> 00:05:28,980
That's fair.

91
00:05:28,980 --> 00:05:32,460
The other thing I remember from that night is that Cory Doctorow was like,

92
00:05:32,460 --> 00:05:34,620
oh my God, can I hold your Hugo?

93
00:05:34,620 --> 00:05:38,020
So that tells you approximately how old this anecdote is.

94
00:05:39,480 --> 00:05:43,280
The Hugo is just a physical representation of things that actually matters,

95
00:05:43,280 --> 00:05:46,840
which is the acclimation of your friends and peers.

96
00:05:46,840 --> 00:05:51,120
What we're interested in is validation emotionally.

97
00:05:51,120 --> 00:05:53,840
We're not interested in physical artifacts on Otto Thorpe.

98
00:05:53,840 --> 00:05:56,160
We are interested in emotional well-being.

99
00:05:56,160 --> 00:06:00,540
So do tell us how marvellous the podcast is because we really care about that.

100
00:06:00,540 --> 00:06:03,960
Please, please tell us how great we are.

101
00:06:03,960 --> 00:06:06,620
I will note also that I am highly materialistic,

102
00:06:06,620 --> 00:06:09,800
so I do achieve my emotional well-being by acquiring more things.

103
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:11,940
So that is a whole conflict of interest.

104
00:06:11,940 --> 00:06:14,340
We should talk about Con Zealand,

105
00:06:14,340 --> 00:06:18,780
because since we last discussed Con Zealand in any great detail,

106
00:06:18,780 --> 00:06:23,760
they have announced what it is they're doing for Worldcon during the pandemic.

107
00:06:23,760 --> 00:06:26,860
So they have a streaming partner,

108
00:06:26,860 --> 00:06:29,320
which is the, and this is a URL,

109
