00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:51,920
Last episode,

192
00:09:51,920 --> 00:09:53,080
or perhaps the episode before,

193
00:09:53,080 --> 00:09:58,480
we were talking about how much you could attend in terms of programming a day.

194
00:09:58,480 --> 00:10:03,900
I think Liz had been on a training course and found it quite exhausting to do eight hours of

195
00:10:03,900 --> 00:10:05,980
content in a single day virtually.

196
00:10:05,980 --> 00:10:08,320
So I'll ask Liz first,

197
00:10:08,320 --> 00:10:14,960
how do you think you can do programming a Worldcon over five days in a way that won't be

198
00:10:14,960 --> 00:10:16,600
exhausting in a similar way?

199
00:10:16,600 --> 00:10:17,260
Well,

200
00:10:17,260 --> 00:10:18,600
I guess the question is,

201
00:10:18,600 --> 00:10:20,280
what do people normally do at Worldcon?

202
00:10:20,280 --> 00:10:25,700
because I think most people do not go and do eight hours of programme on a regular Worldcon day.

203
00:10:25,700 --> 00:10:28,240
And I think it'll be much the same as I would do at a Worldcon,

204
00:10:28,240 --> 00:10:31,800
which is you might pop into one panel or two panels that you really want to see,

205
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:33,160
and then you'll go and have lunch,

206
00:10:33,160 --> 00:10:34,700
and then maybe you'll intend to go to a panel,

207
00:10:34,700 --> 00:10:37,680
but you'll end up hanging out in the bar instead.

208
00:10:37,680 --> 00:10:38,380
And so actually,

209
00:10:38,380 --> 00:10:43,560
you'll go to maybe three or four panels or items and spend the rest of the time chatting to people.

210
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:47,620
I think there are a lot of people who do go to conventions and spend a lot of time in the programme,

211
00:10:47,620 --> 00:10:48,640
literally eight hours,

212
00:10:49,100 --> 00:10:54,400
especially when they first get into fandom and do that gosh, wow, oh boy, oh boy, oh boy thing.

213
00:10:54,400 --> 00:10:58,900
I think your first few conventions, you do in fact hit panels continuously.

214
00:10:58,900 --> 00:10:59,220
I mean,

215
00:10:59,220 --> 00:11:05,780
I still talk to people who have been around a few years who sit there checking off things on a programme book and going,

216
00:11:05,780 --> 00:11:06,900
well, I want to see all these things.

217
00:11:06,960 --> 00:11:09,180
I think even more than usual,

218
00:11:09,180 --> 00:11:13,260
when the Worldcon programme book comes out and people see what's there,

219
00:11:13,260 --> 00:11:17,700
I think you're going to get a lot of people wanting to go to a very large number of sessions.

220
00:11:17,700 --> 00:11:18,520
And I think at that point,

221
00:11:18,520 --> 00:11:28,260
they'll get a flush of people joining as they realise that they can actually see some very exciting people in environments where they wouldn't necessarily otherwise see them.

222
00:11:28,260 --> 00:11:34,900
There are other organisations that already have virtual events of this kind that are very successful.

223
00:11:35,060 --> 00:11:40,480
A lot of gaming and esports things do do virtual conventions and have virtual access.

224
00:11:40,480 --> 00:11:42,320
And they charge quite a lot of money for it.

225
00:11:42,320 --> 00:11:49,520
And people are very happy because they're not incurring the costs of a hotel and all your meals and your travel.

226
00:11:49,520 --> 00:11:54,920
So you get all of that experience of hearing your favourite authors talking to each other,

227
00:11:54,920 --> 00:11:57,240
but without any of the on costs.

228
00:11:57,240 --> 00:12:00,460
And I think for a lot of people, that is quite a good value proposition and it will be fine.

229
00:12:00,460 --> 00:12:04,360
And they will have marvellous programme and people will be amazed by that.

230
00:12:04,700 --> 00:12:06,360
That's my gut feeling.

231
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:08,300
I don't know what they're actually planning to do.

232
00:12:08,300 --> 00:12:13,180
I mean, the other part is that I would usually spend some of that time hanging out in the dealer's room,

233
00:12:13,180 --> 00:12:16,860
looking at things I can't afford to buy, but I can replicate that online.

234
00:12:16,860 --> 00:12:19,840
One thing they are actually planning to do is have a virtual dealer's room.

235
00:12:19,840 --> 00:12:25,940
And I know this because I'm doing a little bit of the playtesting on being a virtual dealer, which is coming up.

236
00:12:25,940 --> 00:12:33,700
The other thing that Liz mentioned is the idea that you would go to a panel and then end up talking to friends in the bar.

